<h1>Step. 5 Assign Players</h1>
<blockquote>
  <p>a.) Players must be assigned to a role. For example, the real student 'John Doe' maybe be assigned to the fictional role of 'UK Prime Minister.' The form shown below is the one you will use to make assignments.</p>
  <blockquote>
    <p><img src="images/tut_sim_conduct_1_page5_assign_user.PNG" alt="Assigning Users" width="718" height="493" /></p>
  </blockquote>
  <p>b.) Assign yourself as a play to all of the roles in your simulation. You do this by following the steps below:</p>
  <ol>
    <ol>
      <li>Enter the user's email address (your email address) in the row for their role.</li>
      <li>Click the 'Assign User' Button for that row.</li>
      <li>If you make a mistake, you can select the button with the minus symbol ('-') to remove an assignment.</li>
      <li>If you need to add addtional players to a role (yes, this is possible) click on the plus symbol ('+') to add an assignment. </li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <p>c.) After you have added some users, the form may look like below. </p>
  <blockquote>
    <p><img src="images/tut_sim_conduct_1_page5_assign_user_done.PNG" alt="Assign Users Done" width="746" height="178" /></p>
    <p>Tip: Rows in pink indicate players that have not been registered on the system.</p>
    <p>Tip: If you are doing this tutorial for an instructor, you may want to add him or her as a player so you can send them an invite to join in the simulation that you have created. </p>
  </blockquote>
  <p>d.) Click on the link 'Next step: Enable Simulation' to move to the next step.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
</blockquote>
